title: State colleges: No. 12 BYU loses in five sets at Loyola Marymount in women's volleyball
text:
Los Angeles • No. 12-ranked BYU had its seven-match win streak snapped, dropping a five-set match to Loyola Marymount — 25-23, 19-25, 25-16, 23-25, 15-12 — in West Coast Conference women's volleyball Saturday night.
Alexa Gray tied a career high with 27 kills to go along with eight digs and five blocks. Only four other BYU players have registered more kills in a game than Gray, whose 67 kill attempts in the match rank third all-time in school history.
"That was a good volleyball match and both teams really wanted it," BYU coach Heather Olmstead said. "I loved our fight in the fourth set and thought we played pretty well for most of the match. We'll get back in the gym and work hard to get better."
  Ciara Parker tallied a season-high 27 digs, and Camry Godfrey Willardson contributed 33 assists and a career-high tying six kills for the Cougars (18-3, 8-2), who had swept their past four opponents entering Saturday's match.
Rachelle Suaava, Sarah Sponcil and Jamie Lee each had 18 kills for Loyola Marymount (15-7, 6-4).
No. 20 Colorado State 3, Utah State 0 • In Logan, the Rams remained undefeated in the Mountain West after sweeping the Aggies 25-18, 25-19, 25-11.
Kayla DeCoursey and Kaylie Kamalu each smashed nine kills; Erica Moscoso tallied 25 assists; and Hannah Gleason recorded 15 digs for Utah State (5-19, 1-9), which has lost nine of its past 10 matches.
"We showed moments of playing with energy tonight," Aggies coach Grayson DuBose said after the match. "We did a nice job defensively, defending on the back row. We just need to find ways to get kills and be more creative that way."
Alex Reid had a match-high 12 kills for Colorado State (17-3, 10-0).
North Dakota 3, Southern Utah 2 • In Cedar City, the visiting Sioux outlasted the Thunderbirds in five grueling sets — 23-25, 25-20, 26-28, 25-23, 19-17 — in Big Sky Conference play.
The teams combined for 153 kills.
Madi Forsythe smashed a match-high 26 kills, and teammate Chennin Benson added 20 for the Thunderbirds (14-9, 5-5), who had won two straight conference games entering Saturday night.
Courtney Place smashed 21 kills and Chelsea Moser had 20 for North Dakota (17-9, 5-5).
Eastern Washington 3, Weber State 0 • In Ogden, the Wildcats led in each set, but couldn't put away the visiting Cougars, who prevailed in straight sets — 25-13, 25-20, 25-18 — in Big Sky Conference action.
Taylor Christensen had 22 assists and Thamires Cavalcanti tallied 11 digs for Weber State (5-15, 1-9), which lost its ninth straight match.
"We need to stop letting things get in the way of our goals of working hard and start being dedicated to winning," Wildcats coach Jeremiah Larsen said. "Until we learn to do that we will not make any progress towards consistency."
Allie Schumacher smashed a match-high 10 kills for Eastern Washington (13-8, 8-2).
Utah Valley 3, Chicago State 0 • In Orem, Lexi Thompson had nine kills and three blocks to lead the Wolverines to their third straight victory — 25-20, 25-16, 25-15 — in Western Athletic Conference play at the PE Building.
